e Canadian state's aspirations as a peacemaker in the postwar world resulted in a series of civilian-military crises that ended only when the scandal of the Somalia Affair in 1993 forced reform. Kasurak offers an illuminating account of the organizational growing pains that wracked the Canada's army as it evolved into a force that could reflect the aspirations of both its country and military leadership.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMilitary history. 7aHISTORY / Military / Canada.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482641940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774826419423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774826419/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles